[b]Trend Persistence Score [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
Trend Persistence Score (TPS) grades how persistent, clean and durable the current trend is on a single 0–100 axis. It fuses four trend-efficiency sensors that all measure the same property — how directly price travels versus how much it chops — into one robust reading. TPS is direction-agnostic by design: the magnitude is the signal, and direction is shown only as visual context.

[b]The four sensors[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Regression R²[/b] — how well price fits a straight line
[*][b]Kaufman Efficiency Ratio[/b] — how directly price travelled over the lookback
[*][b]ADX strength + slope[/b] — trend strength and whether it is building
[*][b]Fractal Dimension[/b] — path roughness (clean trend vs. noisy chop)
[/list]
Each sensor is mapped to a 0–100 sub-score and combined with adjustable role-level weights, so no single sensor can dominate the reading. The per-sensor lines and dashboard show exactly which sensor drives the verdict. Because ADX measures movement rather than directional cleanliness, its sub-score is automatically damped when both structure sensors (R², ER) are weak — raw activity cannot prop up a dead-structure score.

[b]State read[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Trend Strong[/b] / [b]Trend Healthy[/b] — persistent, tradable trend
[*][b]Transition[/b] — trend maturing or losing efficiency
[*][b]Weak / Range[/b] and [b]Trend Dead[/b] — chop; trend-following is unfavourable
[/list]
State changes use one-band hysteresis so the read does not flip on score noise.

[b]Transition Risk[/b]
A second readout derived from TPS estimates how likely the trend is to break down (a low-efficiency tape reads as elevated risk even when ADX lingers). It is a convenience inverse of the persistence score — not a structure-break detector; pair it with a dedicated reversal module for that.

[b]Two-dimensional read[/b]
The oscillator says two things at once: its [b]height[/b] is trend persistence, its [b]colour[/b] is direction (green up-efficiency, red down, grey no clear direction), and its [b]saturation[/b] scales with strength — vivid in a clean trend, pale in a dead market — with an optional heat-column fill to zero. A strong green column reads as a clean uptrend; a fading column as a trend losing power; a shift to red as down-structure forming. Direction is visual only and never enters the score. A Persistence-State colour mode keeps the classic band colours.

[b]Features[/b]
[list]
[*]Calibration anchors (ADX, FDI, ADX-damp threshold/factor) and state levels exposed as inputs
[*]ADX damping when price structure is dead, so movement alone cannot rescue the score
[*]Directional context (▲ Up / ▼ Down / • Flat / • Compress, with measured Bollinger-width compression) — visual only
[*]Light-theme dashboard with full sub-score breakdown
[*]Debug log on every state change
[*]Weakening / Transition / Recovery / Transition-Risk-High alerts
[/list]

[b]How to use[/b]
Use TPS as a trend-following filter (take trend entries only while Healthy/Strong, stand aside in Transition/Dead), or as reversal context (a high score rolling over flags a maturing trend; a Dead reading marks range conditions where mean-reversion logic fits better). Pair it with a direction module for a directional bias.

